<DOC><DOCNO> AP890623-0207 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0134EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-23 0805</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0846</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. economy expanded at a 4.4 percentannual rate in the first three months of the year.   The Commerce Department said Thursday the gross national product,the country's total output of goods and services, rose at thefastest rate in more than a year during the first quarter.   More than half of the increase resulted from a statisticalrebound from last year's drought.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government has ordered tighter screening ofcassette recorders, lap-top computers and other electronic deviceson some international flights, but rejected calls to ban all suchitems from airliners.   Relatives of some of the 270 people killed in the Decemberbombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland had called for the banafter investigators said plastic explosives concealed in a radiocassette player destroyed the plane.   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Thursday a ban wouldunduly inconvenience passengers and would not likely be imposed byother nations.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Wall Street Journal, the nation's firstnational newspaper, is 100 years old.   The nation's largest newspaper, with 2 million circulation, willcelebrate its centennial with a special edition Friday.   A series of birthday bashes held this week cannot obscure thechallenges the paper faces as it heads into its second century:Circulation has slipped, advertising revenue is down and newcompetition has emerged for both readers and ad dollars.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   British conglomerate Hanson Trust PLC has made a$4.8 billion buyout offer for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.   The offer came two months after the mining giant escaped ahostile takeover attempt by another suitor.   Gold Fields quickly advised shareholders not to accept the bidbut indicated it was willing to talk with Hanson, which ownsbusinesses operations ranging from brewing to brickmaking in Britainand the United States.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. partners of the accounting giants ArthurYoung andamp; Co. and Ernst andamp; Whinney have voted overwhelmingly in favorof a previously announced proposal to merge the firms.   The merger plan, which will be submitted to partnerships abroadover the next few months, would create the world's largestprofessional services firm, to be known as Ernst andamp; Young.   The new firm, which will be based in New York, is expected tobegin merged operations by Oct. 1.</TEXT><DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Domino's Pizza Inc. says it plans to stophiring employees under 18 although current workers can stay.   The decision came after Florida parents complained about layoffsfollowing an earlier directive to re-assign or fire drivers under 18.   Domino's has come under fire recently for a series of fatalaccidents involving delivery people. Spokesman Ron Hingst saidThursday Domino's will recommend that its stores not hire peopleunder 18 for driving or non-driving jobs in the future.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Airlines and Delta Air Lines havedropped plans to merge their computer reservation systems becausethe Justice Department threatened to sue to block the $2 billionjoint venture.   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said in a statement announcingthe department's intention to file a civil antitrust suit that amerger would bring higher fares and poorer service.   Delta spokesman William Berry announced that the two carriers hadgiven up trying to merge their computer. ``We decided it would taketoo much time to fight this in court,'' he said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Avon Products Inc. said it has stopped usinganimals in its product safety tests, becoming the first majorcosmetics maker to do so.   Animal rights activists praised Avon and said they hoped thedecision would encourage other companies to completely halt animaltesting.   The beauty products company said it will rely on alternativenon-animal methods, harmless tests on people and an extensivecomputerized data base containing information on the safety ofingredients that previously have been examined.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate has endorsed a Democratic child-carepackage providing low-income parents with subsidies and tax credits,defeating first a White House-backed alternative based almostentirely on tax relief.   The Democratic leadership's victory in the showdown left itsmultibillion-dollar plan as the centerpiece of the Senate'schild-care legislation.   Under an agreement between the parties, the debate continuedThursday on a number of proposed amendments, with Republicansseeking to tack parts of their defeated tax-credit plan ontoDemocratic measure.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market rallied after a three-session slide, recoveringmost of its losses. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained17.26 points to close at 2,482.17.   Bond prices rose despite a decline in the dollar against majorcurrencies.   Also Thursday, sugar futures prices surged; corn and soybeanfutures wilted as rain arrived in Iowa; coffee futures rallied; andenergy, precious-metals and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>